clauses.clause:
The expected results of this policy are as  follows:


  Governance of government security controls within  departments, with partners and across government will be effective, by  fulfilling specified functions and successfully producing the intended result; 
  Access to advice, guidance and services, including  secure internal enterprise services, will be enabled;
  Deputy heads and central agencies will have and share  information needed for informed decision-making on government security  priorities and resources;
  Risk-based and standardized security practices and controls  will be implemented, monitored and maintained; and
  Management of security events will be coordinated to  enable adaptation to a dynamic threat environment.

Deputy heads are responsible for the following: 


  Designating a chief security officer responsible  to the deputy head or to the departmental executive committee to provide  leadership, coordination and oversight for departmental security management activities; 
  Establishing the departmentâs security governance,  including responsibilities for security controls and authorities for security risk  management decisions; 

    Ensuring that their authority to deny, revoke or suspend security clearances is only delegated to the 
    Chief Security Officer
     or 
    Individuals designated by deputy heads of internal enterprise service organizations to oversee their internal enterprise service activities,
     should the deputy head decide to delegate.

  Identifying security and identity management requirements  for all departmental programs and services, considering potential impacts on  internal and external stakeholders;Â  
  Approving a three-year departmental security plan that  is reviewed annually, sets out strategies for meeting departmental security  requirements reflective of and contributing to government-wide security  priorities, and addresses the security controls described in Appendix A; 
  Reviewing any residual security risk that exceeds  established authorities for security risk management decisions;
  Ensuring that security incidents and other security events  are assessed, investigated, documented, acted on and reported to the  appropriate authority and to affected stakeholders; 
  Responding to direction, advice and information  requests issued by the Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat and the Privy  Council Office regarding security events that require an immediate or coordinated  government-wide action; 
  Establishing a written agreement when the department  relies on or supports another department or organization to achieve government  security objectives (see subsectionÂ 6.3 of this policy for application of  this requirement); and
  Investigating  and acting when significant issues regarding policy compliance arise, and  ensuring that appropriate remedial action is taken to address these issues.

Deputy heads of internal enterprise service  organizations, which are departments or organizations that provide internal  enterprise services to other government of Canada departments are responsible  for the following: 


  Establishing governance, including designating one or more senior officials, to oversee security considerations in the provision of internal enterprise  services; 
  Liaising with client departments and the Treasury Board  of Canada Secretariat when identifying security requirements for internal enterprise  services;
  Examining and acting on issues regarding fulfillment of  security requirements with affected stakeholders;
  Conducting periodic reviews (every three years at a  minimum) to assess the extent to which the services provided meet government-wide  security needs; and
  Investigating and acting when significant issues  regarding policy compliance arise, and ensuring that appropriate remedial  action is taken to address these issues.

Deputy heads of lead security agencies, which are described in subsectionÂ 5.2 of  this policy, are responsible for the following: 


  Designating a senior official or officials to oversee  their lead security agency activities under this policy; 
  Consulting with the government-wide security policy  governance when identifying priorities for their lead security agency  activities; 

    Exercising leadership and providing departments with  advice and guidance on government security, in accordance with sectionÂ 5  of this policy and the following general responsibilities:


      Participating in government-wide security policy governance  to assist in setting direction and priorities that align with national security  objectives and other government priorities;
      Providing advice to departments, and developing  technical and operational guidance to support departments in policy  implementation, in accordance with their mandate andÂ in consultation with  the Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat and the government-wide security  policy governance; 
      Consulting with the Treasury Board of Canada  Secretariat, Global Affairs Canada and other relevant lead security agencies  and stakeholders when developing international agreements, treaties or other  instruments that could potentially affect government-wide security management  practices;
      Participating in the analysis of threats,  vulnerabilities, risks and security events; and sharing related findings with  relevant stakeholders; and
      Providing expertise and support for the development of  Government of Canada security awareness and training curricula.

The Secretary of the Treasury Board is  responsible for the following:


  Establishing government-wide security policy  governance to set strategic direction and priorities and coordinating security  priorities, plans and activities government-wide; 
  Representing government-wide security needs in security  governance for internal enterprise services; 
  Liaising with deputy heads and other senior officials on  security issues, including security events that have potential government-wide  impacts;
  Liaising with other lead security agencies on matters  of national security and emergency management; and
  Establishing measures that support the capacity and development  of the security functional community.

Communications  Security Establishment Canada is responsible for the following:


  Serving  as the lead technical authority for information technology (IT) security,  including the provision of leadership, advice, services and guidance for  technical matters related to IT security

  Helping  to ensure the protection of electronic information and of information  infrastructures of importance to the Government of Canada;


    Fulfilling  the following government-wide functions:


      Identifying emerging cyber threats;

      Defending government networks and systems; and 

      Protecting against, and mitigating potential impacts of, cyber  security events;



  Leading  the development of trusted sources of supply for government and critical  infrastructure, and mitigating the risk of untrusted equipment;

  Serving  as the national authority for communications security (COMSEC), including the  procurement, distribution, control and use of cryptographic devices and  encryption keying material for national security systems; and 
  Serving as Canadaâs  national authority for signals intelligence (SIGINT).

National  Defence is responsible for the following:


  Fulfilling  government-wide functions for scientific and technological security research,  defence intelligence, and investigation of security threats to military systems;

  Providing  support to departments in relation to the protection of Government of Canada  officials outside Canada, cyber security, and the provision of other  security-related services;

  Providing  support to Public Safety Canada in relation to the continuity of constitutional  government and domestic counterterrorism;

  Serving  as Canadaâs National Distribution Authority for NATO (North Atlantic Treaty  Organization); and

  Serving  as Canadaâs national authority for Talent-Keyhole (TK) information.

Public Safety  Canada is responsible for the following:


  Providing  leadership, technical advice and guidance for matters related to business  continuity management; 

  Providing  operational leadership for the coordination,  information sharing and situational awareness relating to security events  involving multiple Federal Departments or Agencies that may have  government-wide, intergovernmental, critical infrastructure or national impacts;

  Providing  leadership in establishing the necessary arrangements for the continuity of  constitutional government in the event of an emergency; and 
  Leading coordination and  strategic policy-making on national security and national cyber security  matters.

Public  Services and Procurement Canada is responsible for the following:


  Providing  leadership, advice and guidance for matters related to contract security; 

  Supporting  and fulfilling government-wide functions for issuing personal record identifiers  (PRI) to departments and agencies and individual agency numbers (IAN) to  agencies outside the federal public service, and maintaining the PRI and IAN  systems;

  Providing emergency procurement and emergency accommodation, and providing  security services to help ensure the protection of sensitive information  entrusted to Canadian and foreign industry;

  Providing  internal enterprise services for contract security, base building security for  general-purpose office facilities under its custodial responsibility, and IT security in support of providing and managing certain government-wide  applications; and 

  Serving  as the governmentâs national authority for industrial security, and in this  capacity, serving as Canadaâs Designated Security Authority for NATO.

The Treasury  Board of Canada Secretariat is responsible for the following:


  Establishing and overseeing a  whole-of-government approach to Security management as a key component of all  management activities by ensuring the conduct of periodic reviews of the  effectiveness of security support services, to provide assurance that they  continue to meet the needs of the government as a whole;

  Providing policy leadership,  advice and guidance for all matters related to government Security; 

  Providing strategic policy  oversight and coordination for the management of security events that may  affect the government as a whole.

